Cloud Infrastructure and Monitoring Setup

Overview
A cloud environment on AWS was setup to deploy and monitor honeypots. 
The goal was to create a system where we can run honeypots on an EC2 instance, collect logs, detect suspicios activity, and get alerts. 
EC2 is used for hosting, Docker to run containers, CloudWatch for logging, SNS for alerts, and S3 to store logs securely. 

Architecture
The system is built around an EC2 instance where the honeypots will run using Docker.
Any activity on the system generates logs, which are collected by the Cloudwatch agent. 
These logs are then analyzed using metric filters. 
If something suspicious is detected like an error or failed attempt, a Cloudwatch alarm is triggered and sends an email alert through SNS.
All logs are also stored in an S3 bucket for backup and further analysis. 

EC2 → Docker Honeypot → Logs → CloudWatch → Alarm → SNS → Email
                                   ↓
                                   S3

Implementation Steps 

EC2 Setup
Created EC2 instance (Amazon Linux 2023).
Configured security groups (ports 80, 443, 8080).
Attached IAM role for SSM and CloudWatch.

Docker Setup
Installed Docker
Configured user permissions.
Tested deployment using Nginx container.

Logging (CloudWatch)
Installed CloudWatch agents.
Configured log collection from both /var/log/messages and the honeypot application log file (honeypot.log).
Verified that system logs and honeypot activity logs appeared successfully in CloudWatch Log Groups.

Alerts (SNS + Alarm)
Created SNs topic and subscriptions.
Configured CloudWatch metric filter.
Created CloudWatch metric filters to detect suspicious activity such as errors and login attempts.
Configured CloudWatch alarms to automatically trigger SNS email notifications when suspicious activity was detected.

Storage (S3)
Created secure S3 bucket.
Enabled encryption (SSE-S3).
Enabled versioning for log retention.

Security Measures
Security was implemented using IAM roles for least privilege access, enecrypted storage in S3.
Restricted security group rules, and private log monitoring through CloudWatch.

Testing and Validation
The system was tested by deploying Docker-based honeypot environments and generating suspicious activity such as admin probing, sensitive file access, and simulated login attempts.
These events were successfully written to honeypot logs, monitored through CloudWatch, and used to trigger automated SNS email alerts.
The dashboard correctly displayed hits, alerts, unique IPs, and login attempts across multiple honeypot profiles including Healthcare, Law Firm, and Research Lab.

Conclusion
The final system successfully integrates AWS cloud infrastructure, Docker-based honeypots, centralized logging, automated monitoring, and real-time alerting into a unified cloud security monitoring environment.
The project demonstrates how suspicious activity can be detected, logged, monitored, and escalated automatically using AWS services.

